# Pakistan Blast Risk Analysis & Quadtree Dashboard

*HOW TO RUN:*
    python gui_app.py

**Project Overview**
This project is a high-performance spatial analysis tool designed to identify, visualize, and forecast high-risk zones for suicide blasts across Pakistan. By utilizing a *Quadtree Data Structure*, the program recursively partitions geographical data into optimized "cells" based on incident density. Unlike standard heatmaps, this approach allows for dynamic spatial querying and a mathematically transparent "Heuristic Risk Score" that evaluates areas based on historical frequency, recent trends, and human impact—all without the "black box" of machine learning.

===================
  *data_utils.py* 
===================
WHAT THIS FILE DOES:
  Reads the raw CSV file from disk, removes columns we don't
  need, fixes messy/broken values, and hands back a clean
  table (called a DataFrame) that the rest of the project
  can safely use.

  No machine learning here. No encoding. No sklearn.
  We only keep the columns that the Quadtree and the risk
  heuristic actually need:

    Latitude, Longitude  — to place each incident on the map
    Year                 — for recency weighting
    Province             — for labels and demo mode
    Killed Max           — for the severity part of the score
    Injured Max          — extra context shown to the user
    Location Category    — shown in the risk profile report
    Target Type          — shown in the risk profile report

DATA FLOW:
  CSV file on disk
       |
       v
  load_and_clean_data()   <- you are here
       |
       v
  clean DataFrame  --->  spatial_engine.py  (builds the Quadtree)
                   --->  risk_calculator.py (scores every cell)
                   --->  main_app.py        (shows results to user)

==================================================================================================================================

=======================
  *spatial_engine.py* 
=======================

How a node is stored:
  Every cell (called a "node") is just a Python dictionary:
  {
    "lat_min"  : float   southern edge of this cell
    "lat_max"  : float   northern edge
    "lon_min"  : float   western edge
    "lon_max"  : float   eastern edge
    "depth"    : int     0 = the whole country, 6 = smallest cell
    "cell_id"  : int     unique ID number (assigned after building)
    "incidents": list    list of incident dicts stored in this cell
    "children" : list    4 child dicts if this cell was split, else []
  }

How an incident is stored:
  Each incident inside a node is also a Python dictionary:
  {
    "row_idx"  : int     row number from the original DataFrame
    "lat"      : float   GPS latitude
    "lon"      : float   GPS longitude
    "year"     : int     year the blast happened
    "label"    : str     province name
    "killed"   : float   Killed Max from the dataset
    "injured"  : float   Injured Max from the dataset
  }

CRUD Operations (Create, Read, Update, Delete):
  CREATE  ->  insert_incident(), build_quadtree()
  READ    ->  find_leaf_node(), get_all_leaf_nodes(), get_incidents_in_region(), count_incidents()
  UPDATE  ->  update_incident()
  DELETE  ->  delete_incident()


==================================================================================================================================

========================
  *risk_calculator.py* 
========================
Formula to calculate risk: SCORE = (Density_Score + Depth_Score + Recency_Score + Severity_Score)   capped at 100

  1. DENSITY SCORE  (max 40 points)
     Counts how many incidents are packed into this cell.
     Smaller cell + more incidents = higher score.
     Formula:  min(count * 5,  40)

  2. DEPTH SCORE  (max 20 points)
     A deep cell means the tree HAD to split many times to
     fit the incidents — so the area is a chronic hotspot.
     Formula:  min(depth * 3,  20)

  3. RECENCY SCORE  (max 25 points)
     Incidents from the last 2 years count DOUBLE compared
     to incidents from long ago.
     Formula:  min(recent_count * 4  +  old_count * 2,  25)

  4. SEVERITY SCORE  (max 15 points)
     Total people killed in this cell.  
     More deaths = higher risk of future severity.
     Formula:  min(total_killed * 0.1,  15)

RISK BANDS (for colour coding):
  80–100  CRITICAL  (dark red)
  60–79   HIGH      (red)
  40–59   MEDIUM    (orange)
  20–39   LOW       (yellow)
   0–19   MINIMAL   (green)

TREND FORECAST:
  Compares incident counts across 3 time windows.
  If count is rising   →  "ESCALATING"
  If count is falling  →  "DE-ESCALATING"
  If roughly stable    →  "STABLE"

DATA FLOW:
  spatial_engine.py (Quadtree root)
       |
       v
  calculate_node_risk(node, current_year)   -> score 0..100
  get_risk_band(score)                       -> label + colour
  get_risk_profile(node, current_year)       -> full stats dict
  calculate_all_cell_risks(root, year)       -> {cell_id: score}
  get_trend(node, current_year)              -> trend string
  generate_forecast_frames(root, ...)        -> PNG files

==================================================================================================================================

=============================
  *gui_app.py: Tkinter GUI* 
=============================
WHAT THIS FILE DOES:
    Opens a graphical window with 4 tabs:
      1. MAP        — live Quadtree map, click any cell to read it
      2. CRUD       — Add, Update, Delete incidents with live map refresh
      3. FORECAST   — 5-year risk prediction per cell
      4. STATS      — Summary numbers and top-10 risk table


